ce targets means that managers should take responsibility for and believe in the targets set for them. This increases their commitment to achieving these targets.\"", "\"ACHIEVABILITY\":\"Achievability refers to setting performance targets that are challenging yet attainable, motivating managers to strive for them without feeling overwhelmed.\"", "\"EQUITY\":\"Equity in performance measurement means maintaining fairness and unbiased assessment across all business areas, ensuring that targets are realistic and comparable.\"", "\"CLARITY\":\"Clarity in reward schemes means that employees must understand the performance measurement criteria and how their performance will be evaluated.\"", "\"CONTROLLABILITY\":\"Controllability refers to the principle that managers should be evaluated based on factors they can control, ensuring fair and accurate performance assessments.\"", "\"MOTIVATION\":\"Motivation\" in the context of participative budgeting refers to encouraging managers to perform well by involving them in the budget-setting process. When managers believe the budget is realistic, they are more likely to strive to achieve it. Additionally, motivation in the context of reward schemes means that bonuses and incentives should encourage employees to achieve their performance targets.", "\"FITZGERALD AND MOON MODEL\":\"The Fitzgerald and Moon model identifies six dimensions of performance that organizations should measure: financial performance, competitiveness, quality, resource utilization, flexibility, and innovation. It is similar to the balanced scorecard model.\"", "\"EXAMPLE 2 CAR DEALER'S PERFORMANCE\":\"This example illustrates how a large car dealer network in the UK uses various performance dimensions and measures, such as financial performance, competitiveness, quality of service, and resource utilization, to assess and improve its operations.\"", "\"REWARD SCHEMES\":\"Reward schemes are systems that link performance to compensation, such as bonuses, to motivate managers to achieve their targets. Key principles include clarity, motivation, and controllability.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF BUILDING BLOCK MODEL\":\"This example describes how SmartC, a package delivery company, applies the building block model to measure and improve its performance across various dimensions, including financial performance, competitiveness, quality, flexibility, innovation, and resource utilization.\"", "\"PERFORMANCE\":", "\"FLEXIBILITY OF SERVICE\":\"Flexibility of service refers to a company's ability to meet customer demands and preferences. It can be measured by targets such as the percentage of orders scheduled to customers' requests.\"", "\"REWARDS\":\"Rewards refer to the compensation package provided to employees, which can include financial and non-financial benefits. Effective reward systems contribute to employee motivation by meeting their different needs and linking rewards to performance.\"", "\"TYPES OF NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATION\":\"The non-profit sector includes public sector bodies like schools and hospitals, not-for-profit (NFP) organizations, and non-governmental organizations (NGOs). These organizations typically do not have profit as their primary objective and focus on providing public goods and services.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF STATE-FUNDED UNIVERSITY\":\"A state-funded university is accountable to multiple stakeholders with potentially conflicting objectives, such as students desiring small class sizes and the government wanting to minimize costs per student. Designing a performance measurement system for such an institution is complex.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}